==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mate
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mater</ets> to fatigue,
enfeeble, humiliate, checkmate. See <er>Mate</er> checkmate.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To confuse; to confound.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To checkmate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mate
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perhaps for older <ets>make</ets> a
companion; cf. also OD. <ets>maet</ets> companion, mate, D.
<ets>maat</ets>. Cf. <er>Make</er> a companion, <er>Match</er> a
mate.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who customarily associates with
another; a companion; an associate; any object which is associated or
combined with a similar object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, a husband or wife; and among
the lower animals, one of a pair associated for propagation and the care
of their young.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A suitable companion; a match; an equal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye knew me once no <qex>mate</qex>⟦br⟧
For you; there sitting where you durst not soar.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An officer in a merchant vessel
ranking next below the captain. If there are more than one bearing the
title, they are called, respectively, <xex>first mate</xex>, <xex>second
mate</xex>, <xex>third mate</xex>, etc. In the navy, a subordinate
officer or assistant; <as>as, master's <ex>mate</ex>; surgeon's
<ex>mate</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Mate
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To match; to
marry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If she be <qex>mated</qex> with an equal husband.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To match one's self against; to oppose as equal; to
compete with.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is no passion in the mind of man so weak but it
<qex>mates</qex> and masters the fear of death.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, . . . in the way of loyalty and truth, . . .⟦br⟧
Dare <qex>mate</qex> a sounder man than Surrey can be.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To breed; to bring (animals) together for the
purpose of breeding; <as>as, she <ex>mated</ex> a doberman with a German
shepherd</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To join together; to fit together; to connect; to
link; <as>as, he <ex>mated</ex> a saw blade to a broom handle to cut
inaccessible branches.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Mate
<hw>Mate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be or become a mate or mates,
especially in sexual companionship; <as>as, some birds <ex>mate</ex> for
life; this bird will not <ex>mate</ex> with that one.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mated</ent>⟦br⟧
